{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17478956","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17478956"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:17:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:17:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18893"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18893","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18893"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.03,0.14,0.22,0.47]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11626"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107275"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11626","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11626"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18893"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89736"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1308"},{"type":"tags","id":"2776"},{"type":"tags","id":"2780"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"8825"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27356"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39572"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107275","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107275"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA three-month-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his parent who is concerned about excessive tearing from both eyes since birth. The parent also reports that the child frequently squeezes his eyes shut in the light, and has tears from his eyes when not crying. He was born at term with no complications and has no other medical conditions. He does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His corneas appear enlarged and hazy, and there is no redness of the conjunctivae. The parent mentions that the child\u0027s eyes seem larger than those of other infants of the same age. He is smiling but not sitting upright unsupported.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sturge-Weber syndrome","Neurofibromatosis","Corneal dystrophy","Nasolacrimal duct obstruction","Congenital glaucoma"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis infant presents with the classic triad of symptoms associated with congenital glaucoma: photophobia (light sensitivity), epiphora (excessive tearing), and blepharospasm (squeezing of eyelids) due to increased intraocular pressure. The finding of enlarged, hazy corneas is particularly significant and characteristic of this condition when the intraocular pressure is over 30-40mmHg.  Though brief, there was no signs of developmental delay.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECongenital glaucoma\u003C/strong\u003E is caused by developmental abnormalities of the anterior chamber angle leading to increased intraocular pressure. Primary congenital glaucoma can present at newborn, as an infant (1-24 months) or late onset (more than 24 months) but typically presents in the first 9 months. It can follow an autosomal recessive inheritance or be sporadic, and appears more common in cases of consanguinity. Early recognition and prompt referral to an ophthalmologist is crucial as delayed treatment can lead to permanent vision loss.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESturge-Weber syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E can cause secondary glaucoma but is typically associated with a facial port-wine stain and leptomeningeal angiomas. The glaucoma in Sturge-Weber syndrome is usually unilateral and corresponds to the side of the facial nevus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeurofibromatosis\u003C/strong\u003E can have ocular manifestations but these typically include Lisch nodules and optic pathway gliomas rather than the presenting features in this case. Other characteristic findings such as caf\u00e9-au-lait spots would be expected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENasolacrimal duct obstruction\u003C/strong\u003E can cause excessive tearing but typically does not cause photophobia or corneal changes. It is usually unilateral and associated with mucoid discharge and crusting of the eyelids.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECorneal dystrophy\u003C/strong\u003E can cause corneal haziness but typically does not present with enlargement of the cornea or the classic triad of symptoms seen in this case. Most corneal dystrophies become apparent later in life.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Classic triad of congenital glaucoma includes photophobia, epiphora and blepharospasm.","Enlarged corneal diameter (\u003E12mm) and corneal haziness are key examination findings in congenital glaucoma.","Early recognition and referral of congenital glaucoma is crucial as delayed treatment can lead to permanent vision loss."],"references":["Ashraf G, Chakrabarti R. Paediatric photophobia: The pressure of a timely diagnosis. Aust J Gen Pract. 2021 Oct;50(10):741\u20135. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2021/october/paediatric-photophobia","Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Melbourne. Childhood glaucoma information sheet. Published 2019. Available at: https://www.rch.org.au/uploadedFiles/Main/Content/ophthal/Childhood%20Glaucoma%20Information%20Sheet.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89736"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18893"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89736","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89736"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-27T11:05:46+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-27T11:07:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11626"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107275"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/ta